@flexiarg aif/niche-construction
@title Niche Construction as the Bootstrap Loop of an Inference Agent
@sigils [🐜/巢]
@keywords niche-construction, bootstrap, typed-edge-inventory, false-floor, substrate, generative-model, anamnesis, mana, agency, action-class, ΔT
@audience operators of fulab / futon-stack agents, mission authors, designers of read/write substrates for an active-inference engine
@references [aif/expected-free-energy-scorecard aif/structured-observation-vector futon-theory/structural-tension-as-observation]
@references-extra ["Lewontin (1983) on niche construction in biology" "Odling-Smee, Laland, Feldman (2003) Niche Construction: The Neglected Process in Evolution" "Friston (2010, 2017) on active inference and policy selection over external structure" "Andy Clark (1997, 2008) on scaffolded cognition and extended mind" "Mission of origin: ~/code/futon3c/holes/missions/M-action-cost-modelling.md §3.8 + §5.1 T9 closure (2026-05-27 emacs-repl, claude-1 + Joe)"]
@tone declarative
@style pattern

! conclusion: An inference agent cannot construct its own niche; the agents operating its peripherals do, and the agent's false-floor readings are how those agents know what to construct.

  + context: An active-inference agent (e.g. the futon War Machine) reads a substrate of typed vertices and edges, computes T / ∇T / ΔT or analogues, and ranks actions. Its inference is bounded by the typed-edge inventory of the substrate it can see. The substrate is itself authored by other agents and operators.

  + IF:
    You are designing an AIF agent whose generative model depends on a structured substrate (hypergraph, knowledge graph, typed event log) that is authored by parties other than the agent itself.

  + HOWEVER:
    The agent cannot extend its own substrate's typed-edge inventory — it has operations on values within the niche but not on the meta-level structure of the niche. When action classes surface that the inventory doesn't cover, the agent reads ΔT = 0 (false floor), not error. It looks confident-and-wrong; it is in fact correctly-uninformed, and the substrate is incomplete.

  + THEN:
    Treat false-floor readings as **niche-construction signals**, not bugs. Each false-floor names a typed-edge family the substrate is missing relative to the action classes agents actually take. The operators-and-agents who use the inference agent do the niche construction: they add the missing typed-edge families, ingest the missing vertex types, derive the missing relations. On the next tick the agent sees a richer niche and ranks more accurately.

  + BECAUSE:
    Niche construction (Lewontin 1983; Odling-Smee / Laland / Feldman 2003; Friston in active-inference terms) is the loop by which an organism modifies its environment so its inference becomes tractable. The futon agent is in the same loop; only the niche is symbolic (a typed graph) rather than physical. Confident false-floors masquerading as signal is the worst outcome — the agent makes apparently-warranted-but-actually-uninformed choices. Visible false-floors that operators can read as "edges missing here" is the right outcome — the agent's blindness becomes the input to its own niche's improvement.

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Surface false-floor readings as such — don't silently zero-out a signal; report "ΔT = 0 (no incident edges of supported family)" so absence is legible to operators.
    - When new action classes are added to a ranking surface, audit which typed-edge families would feed ΔT (or analogue) for that class, and which are present-vs-missing in the substrate.
    - For the futon stack as of 2026-05-27: the WM's ΔT over `code/v05/related-mission` works for sorry-actions but gives ΔT = 0 false-floor for anchor-reframe / file-edit / excursion-step actions. Construction backlog: (a) feed `code/v05/mission-cross-ref` (already in substrate from M-weird-modernism Task 8 single-parser consolidation) into the Laplacian; (b) derive `code/v05/file → mission` from `:mission/code-paths`; (c) ingest E-prefix excursion docs as a typed vertex family (currently not ingested).
    - Connection to aliveness synthesis (M-action-cost-modelling §3.8): anamnesis = un-discharged tension drives niche construction; niche construction discharges anamnesis into mana. The three terms form a single loop, with niche construction as the operative mechanism by which agent-substrate aliveness shifts.
    - Sibling-pattern dependency: when authoring missions that ship new action classes, the mission's INSTANTIATE phase should explicitly enumerate the niche-construction-audit per class (which edges feed the Laplacian, which are absent). Treat per-class niche-construction state as first-class mission metadata, not implicit.
